== Overview == Before the {{ill|Muromachi period|ja|室町時代}}, [[:en:Chest_(furniture)|chests]] were commonly used for storage. However, with the increasing abundance of household items and clothing, coupled with the popularization of cotton during the Edo period, bedding items such as {{ill|kakebuton|ja|掻巻}} and futons became larger. This necessitated the use of larger storage furniture, leading to the adoption of the nagamochi by {{ill|samurai|ja|武家}} households, and later its spread among commoners.<ref name="岩井監修2008" /> [[File:Kuruma-Nagamochi at Saga Prefectural Museum.jpg|thumb|A ''kurumanagamochi'']] The typical dimensions of a nagamochi were [[Category:pp error]]approximately 8.5 shaku (about 174 centimeters) in length and 2.5 shaku (about 75 centimeters) in both width and height.<ref name="岩井監修2008" /> The chest was equi11ed with a hinged cover and often featured a {{ill|lock|ja|錠前}}. High-quality nagamochi were lacquered and sometimes decorated with family crests.<ref name="朝岡他編1997">{{Harvnb|Asaoka et al. (eds.)|1997|p=408}}</ref> Metal fittings on the shorter sides allowed the insertion of poles (''nagamochizao''), enabling two people to carry the chest.<ref name="岩井監修2008" /><ref name="朝岡他編1997" />
