[[sn:Nagamochi]]
[[ja:長持]]

<!--Nagamochi--><!--Nagamochi--><!--Nagamochi--><!--Nagamochi--><!--Nagamochi--><!--Nagamochi--><!--Nagamochi--><!--Nagamochi--><!--Nagamochi--><!--Nagamochi-->

{{Otheruses|folk implements|place name in Hiratsuka City|Nagamochi (Hiratsuka City)}}
[[File:Shohakuken_Nagamochi.jpg|right|thumb|200px|Illustration of a nagamochi from Okuda Shōhakuken's *Nyōyō Kunmō Zui*]]
A '''nagamochi''' (長持) is a type of rectangular wooden chest used primarily during the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]] in Japan for storing items such as {{ill|clothing|ja|衣類|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/clothing|qq=}} and [[:en:Bedding|bedding]].<ref name="岩井監修2008">{{Harvnb|Iwai (ed.)|2008|p=197}}</ref> When wheels were attached to its base to improve mobility, it was referred to as a ''kurumanagamochi'' (車長持).

== Overview ==
Before the [[:en:Muromachi period|Muromachi period]], [[:en:Chest_(furniture)|chests]] were commonly used for storage. However, with the increasing abundance of household items and clothing, coupled with the popularization of cotton during the Edo period, bedding items such as {{ill|kakebuton|ja|掻巻|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kakebuton|qq=}} and futons became larger. This necessitated the use of larger storage furniture, leading to the adoption of the nagamochi by {{ill|samurai|ja|武家|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/samurai|qq=}} households, and later its spread among commoners.<ref name="岩井監修2008" />
[[File:Kuruma-Nagamochi at Saga Prefectural Museum.jpg|thumb|A ''kurumanagamochi'']]
The typical dimensions of a nagamochi were approximately 8.5 shaku (about 174 centimeters) in length and 2.5 shaku (about 75 centimeters) in both width and height.<ref name="岩井監修2008" /> The chest was equi11ed with a hinged cover and often featured a [[:en:Lock and key|lock]]. High-quality nagamochi were lacquered and sometimes decorated with family crests.<ref name="朝岡他編1997">{{Harvnb|Asaoka et al. (eds.)|1997|p=408}}</ref> Metal fittings on the shorter sides allowed the insertion of poles (''nagamochizao''), enabling two people to carry the chest.<ref name="岩井監修2008" /><ref name="朝岡他編1997" />

The ''kurumanagamochi,'' fitted with wheels for easier transport, gained popularity. However, after the devastating [[:en:Great Fire of Meireki|Great Fire of Meireki]] in Edo (modern-day Tokyo) in [[:en:1657|1657]], the use of these wheeled chests was banned in Edo, Kyoto, and Osaka due to their tendency to congest roads during evacuations.<ref name="岩井監修2008" /> Nonetheless, their use persisted in rural areas. For instance, during fires in [[:en:Sendai|Sendai]] in [[:en:1754|1754]] (Hōreki 4), ''kurumanagamochi'' were still being moved through the streets.<ref>{{Harvnb|Yoshida (ed.)|2007|p=96}}</ref>

Nagamochi were also traditional items in bridal dowries. Songs sung during the transport of nagamochi as part of wedding celebrations, known as ''nagamochi songs'' (長持歌), have been passed down through generations. However, by the [[:en:Meiji era|Meiji period]] and {{ill|Taishō period|ja|大正時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishō period|qq=}}, the nagamochi was largely replaced by the [[:en:Commode|tansu]].<ref name="朝岡他編1997" />

